04966nam a22006855i 9780824839055DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248390557 a10.1515/97808248390552doi  a(DE-B1597)484462  a(OCoLC)867741730  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0040002bisacsh04a910.9164822300aMutiny and Aftermath :bJames Morrison's Account of the Mutiny on the Bounty and the Island of Tahiti /ced. by Vanessa Smith, Maia Nuku, Nicholas Thomas. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b27 illus., 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Journal: Mutiny, Mutineers, Islanders -- t1. The Voyage and the Mutiny -- t2. The Occupation of Tubuai -- t3. Return to Tahiti -- t4. From Tahiti to England -- tPart II. The Account: The Island of Tahiti -- t5. The Tahitian World -- t6. Tahitian Society, History, and Culture -- t7. Arts, Rites, and Customs -- tAppendix I: Morrison’s Polynesian Words and Terms -- tAppendix II: Morrison’s People -- tAppendix III: Morrison’s Place-names -- tAppendix IV: Morrison’s Plants -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Editors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe mutiny on the Bounty was one of the most controversial events of eighteenth-century maritime history. This book publishes a full and absorbing narrative of the events by one of the participants, the boatswain's mate James Morrison, who tells the story of the mounting tensions over the course of the voyage out to Tahiti, the fascinating encounter with Polynesian culture there, and the shocking drama of the event itself.In the aftermath, Morrison was among those who tried to make a new life on Tahiti. In doing so, he gained a deeper understanding of Polynesian culture than any European who went on to write about the people of the island and their way of life before it was changed forever by Christianity and colonial contact. Morrison was not a professional scientist but a keen observer with a lively sympathy for Islanders. This is the most insightful and wide-ranging of early European accounts of Tahitian life.Mutiny and Aftermath is the first scholarly edition of this classic of Pacific history and anthropology. It is based directly on a close study of Morrison’s original manuscript, one of the treasures of the Mitchell Library in Sydney, Australia. The editors assess and explain Morrison’s observations of Islander culture and social relations, both on Tubuai in the Austral Islands and on Tahiti itself. The book fully identifies the Tahitian people and places that Morrison refers to and makes this remarkable text accessible for the first time to all those interested in an extraordinary chapter of early Pacific history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBounty Mutiny, 1789. 7aHISTORY / Australia & New Zealand.2bisacsh1 aNuku, Maia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Vanessa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThomas, Nicholas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483905540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824839055423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824839055/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066325-9  Unive